library(dplyr) library(readr) company<-"^HSI" stDt <- as.Date(Sys.time()) endDt <- as.Date("2022-06-30") expctdAnnRtrn<-0.0 #expected market return - did I mention I'm a pessimist? r<-exp(log(1+expctdAnnRtrn)/365)-1 remainingCloses<-sum(!weekdays(seq(stDt, endDt, "days")) %in% c("Saturday", "Sunday")) forecastBands <- c(-Inf,20000,23000,26000,29000,32000,Inf) histData<-read_csv( paste0( "https://query1.finance.yahoo.com/v7/finance/download/" , company , "?period1=946684800&period2=" , floor(as.numeric(as.POSIXct(Sys.time()))) , "&interval=1d&events=history&includeAdjustedClose=true" ) ) pricehistory<-as.numeric(histData$`Adj Close`) pricehistory<-pricehistory[!is.na(pricehistory)] spot<-pricehistory[length(pricehistory)] sdMovementRatio <- sd(log(pricehistory[1:length(pricehistory)-1]/pricehistory[2:(length(pricehistory))])) simulation<-spot*replicate(10000, cumprod(exp(rnorm( remainingCloses,mean = r, sd = sdMovementRatio )))[remainingCloses]) cutSimulation<-as_tibble(cut(simulation,forecastBands)) mutate(count(cutSimulation,value),n/sum(n))
Best guess after a quick look at the chart.
Stochastic simulation

So I'm using 12 years of historical data and I generated a Monte Carlo (backtesting) estimate. This is a random walk model. Now I'm laying on some hypotheses to that distribution: 1) I think the Communist Party is trying to reduce inequality, and doesn't want the market skyrocketing. 2) I think that Chinese companies will be doing worse financially, now that they are making 'donations' to fund the Communist Party's goals. 3) I think that Chinese entrepreneurialism has been deflated to some degree, by the many changes imposed on profitable industries. 4) I think there are systemic problems (i.e. overinvestment in real estate), and deflating the real estate debt bubble is going to be a headwind for the economy. As a result, I'm tightening my distribution as compared to history (most of the data was collected in a volatile environment which maximized entrepreneurialism and profit-seeking), and centering my distribution around today's price of 25000 and reducing by 5%.

Created a quick dirty normal graph of the yearly changes each year from yahoo finance from 1987. Average is 18% and std deviation 38% (which seems extremely volatile). Because June is half a year away, I just did half and plotted out those values. Not sure if I should remove the first 5 years because of the >50 increases each year.
Fear of what beijing will do should keep it from rising much. Also a possibility of a mass panic and exodus of money that would take it even lower.
Estimated from the prior 5 years of stock price history (prior max of ~30,500 is noted for future reference).
Like all stock exchanges this is a bit of a lottery, which means I should avoid forecasting as likely to be really wrong. But like any free bet, its always fun.
